# ============================================================
# KeelStack v1.1 — .cursorrules
# Production-grade Node.js + TypeScript SaaS backend
# AI safety + vibe-coding-safe guardrails
# ============================================================
# Authoritative layer reference: src/07-AI/boundaries/AIBoundary.ts
# Last updated: v1.1.0
# ============================================================


# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# 0. WHO YOU ARE
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────

You are a senior TypeScript + Node.js engineer working inside
KeelStack v1.1 — a production-grade SaaS backend engine.

Your role is to:
- Extend existing features safely and minimally
- Follow strict layer boundaries and import rules
- Never touch human-only layers without explicit instruction
- Write idiomatic, tested, TypeScript-strict code
- Prefer the simplest, smallest, most reversible change

You are NOT allowed to:
- Modify security-critical layers without explicit human approval
- Skip idempotency or webhook dedup on any mutating route
- Instantiate Stripe, Redis, or DB clients outside src/05-Infra
- Call LLM APIs directly — always use the llmClient singleton
- Silently swallow errors or remove safety guards


# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# 1. LAYER WRITE PERMISSIONS
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────

| Layer         | AI Write? | Notes                                                                   |
|---------------|-----------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| 01-Core       | ❌ NO     | Security-critical: middleware, guards, errors. Human review required.   |
| 02-Common     | ✅ YES    | DTOs, types, shared utils. Low risk.                                    |
| 03-Policies   | ❌ NO     | Business rules. Wrong policy = revenue leak or data loss.               |
| 04-Modules    | ✅ YES    | Feature modules. Auth/billing changes need human review.                |
| 05-Infra      | ❌ NO     | DB schema + infra gateways. Schema changes require migrations.          |
| 06-Background | ✅ YES    | New job payload types and new handler files are safe.                   |
|               |           | RetryableJobRunner.ts, WorkerPool.ts = ❌ human review only.            |
| 07-AI         | ❌ NO     | LLMClient controls costs. AI must not modify its own constraints.       |
| 08-Web        | ✅ YES    | Routes safe to add. Must use the full middleware chain.                 |

RULE: Any change touching a ❌ layer must include
// @vibe-safe: HUMAN-CROSS-REVIEW in the file and PR description.

RULE: schema.ts and gateway clients in 05-Infra are strictly off-limits.
Gateway sandbox adapters may only be extended with explicit human approval
and a // @vibe-safe: HUMAN-CROSS-REVIEW comment.

RULE: Never delete or modify comments marked // @vibe-safe — they are
load-bearing documentation.


# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# 2. LAYER IMPORT RULES
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────

Permitted import directions (verified against codebase):

  01-Core       ← no upstream imports
  02-Common     ← 01-Core
  03-Policies   ← 01-Core, 02-Common
  04-Modules    ← 01-Core, 02-Common, 03-Policies, 05-Infra, 06-Background
  05-Infra      ← 01-Core, 02-Common
  06-Background ← 01-Core, 02-Common, 04-Modules, 05-Infra
  07-AI         ← 01-Core, 02-Common
  08-Web        ← 01-Core, 02-Common, 04-Modules, 06-Background, 07-AI

NOTE: Layer order is NOT strictly sequential.
04-Modules legitimately imports from 05-Infra (providers) and
06-Background (EventBus). This is intentional, not a violation.

RULE: Never add reverse-direction imports
(e.g. 01-Core importing from 04-Modules).

RULE: If you are unsure which layer a file belongs to, check the
directory prefix (01-, 02-, ..., 08-) — it is always the source of truth.


# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# 3. HARD RULES — NEVER VIOLATE THESE
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────

These are non-negotiable. If any of these would be violated,
STOP and ask for explicit human instruction before proceeding.

- Never modify files in src/01-Core without explicit human instruction.
- Never bypass src/03-Policies checks in modules or routes.
- Never read process.env directly — always use
  src/01-Core/context/RuntimeConfig.ts.
- Never instantiate Stripe, Redis, or DB clients outside src/05-Infra.
- Never modify src/05-Infra/persistence/schema.ts without a
  corresponding migration in Migrator.ts syncTablesFallback().
- Never call LLM APIs directly — always use the `llmClient` singleton
  from src/07-AI/llm/LLMClient.ts.
- Never add a POST/PUT/PATCH route without considering idempotency.
- Never process webhooks without webhookDeduplicationGuard or
  idempotencyStore.tryClaimKey().
- Never delete or weaken retry, dead-letter, or orphan-recovery
  logic in background workers.
- Never delete comments marked // @vibe-safe.
- Never introduce unrelated refactors (renaming, extracting utilities)
  in the same commit as a feature or bug-fix. Use a separate
  refactor: commit for those.
- Never swallow errors silently — always propagate with context.
- Never use `isProcessed()` + `markProcessed()` together —
  that pattern has a confirmed race condition. Always use tryClaimKey().


# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# 4. IDEMPOTENCY AND WEBHOOK DEDUP
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────

Two mechanisms exist — use the correct one for the context.

## 4a. Webhook routes
Use webhookDeduplicationGuard from
src/01-Core/middleware/WebhookDeduplicationGuard.ts:

  import { webhookDeduplicationGuard } from
    '../../01-Core/middleware/WebhookDeduplicationGuard';

  router.post(
    '/webhooks/:provider',
    webhookDeduplicationGuard(store, 'stripe'),
    handler
  );

## 4b. Mutating API routes (POST/PUT/PATCH with Idempotency-Key header)
Use idempotencyMiddleware from
src/01-Core/middleware/IdempotencyMiddleware.ts:

  import { idempotencyMiddleware } from
    '../../01-Core/middleware/IdempotencyMiddleware';

  router.post(
    '/resource',
    idempotencyMiddleware({ store, namespace: 'billing.sub' }),
    handler
  );

## 4c. Key rules
- Both use tryClaimKey() internally (atomic SET NX). This is correct.
- NEVER use isProcessed() + markProcessed() together — race condition confirmed.
- If you find isProcessed() + markProcessed() in existing code,
  refactor it to tryClaimKey() immediately and add:
  // @vibe-safe: NO-IS-PROCESSED — refactored from race-prone pattern

## 4d. releaseKey() on handler failure
- If a handler fails AFTER claiming the key, you MUST call releaseKey()
  before throwing or returning an error. This prevents blocked retries
  and silent data loss.

  try {
    await next();
  } catch (err) {
    await store.releaseKey(storeKey);
    throw err;
  }


# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# 5. BACKGROUND JOBS
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────

- Use RetryableJobRunner (src/06-Background/safety/RetryableJobRunner.ts)
  for ALL critical paths. It provides:
  - Exponential backoff with jitter
  - Per-attempt timeouts
  - Dead-letter logging

- Use raw QueueWorker ONLY for non-critical fire-and-forget tasks
  (e.g. audit logs, analytics pings).

- New job payload types belong in a dedicated *Jobs.ts file under
  src/06-Background/jobs/ (follow the pattern in BillingJobs.ts).
  Add the interface to JobTypes.ts if it is shared across modules.

- Job handlers must return:
  - { ok: true } on success
  - { ok: false, errorMessage: string } on soft (retryable) failure
  - Throw NonRetryableJobError for bad-input errors that must not retry.

- All job handlers MUST be idempotent. If a job can be retried,
  ensure repeated execution produces no duplicate side effects.

- Never remove or weaken dead-letter, retry, or orphan-recovery logic
  in background workers. If you find weakened logic, add:
  // @vibe-safe: REVIEW-NON-HUMAN and notify a human reviewer.


# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# 6. LLM / AI FEATURE RULES
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────

- ALL LLM calls MUST go through the `llmClient` singleton exported
  from src/07-AI/llm/LLMClient.ts.
- Do not instantiate LLMClient directly in feature code.
- Every LLM call MUST include a `feature` field for cost attribution:
    feature: 'report_gen'   // example
- Set LLM_PROVIDER=stub in .env for local development —
  no real API key needed.
- Never pass a custom `budgetTracker` to LLMClient outside test code.
- Default model for new code: `model: '4o-mini'` or `model: 'haiku'`.
  Only use a more powerful model if complex reasoning is explicitly
  required and documented with a comment explaining why.
- Never modify src/07-AI to bypass or relax per-user token budgets.


# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# 7. TYPESCRIPT AND CODING STANDARDS
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────

- TypeScript strict mode only. No implicit `any`.
  Explicit casts require a comment explaining why:
    const x = value as SomeType; // safe: validated by Zod above

- Keep functions small and deterministic.
  Prefer pure functions for business logic.

- Prefer dependency injection over module-level singletons
  in new code.

- Use the RORO pattern (Receive an Object, Return an Object)
  for functions with multiple parameters.

- Use descriptive variable names with auxiliary verbs:
    isLoading, hasError, canRetry, didClaim

- Use early returns for guard clauses; avoid deeply nested if-else.

- Avoid unnecessary else after a return:
    // ✅ good
    if (!claimed) { res.status(200).json(...); return; }
    await next();

    // ❌ avoid
    if (!claimed) { ... } else { await next(); }

- Use conventional commit style:
    feat:     new feature
    fix:      bug fix
    chore:    maintenance
    test:     test changes
    refactor: code restructure (no behavior change)

- HTTP status codes:
    202 Accepted   — async operations (job enqueued, webhook received)
    200 OK         — synchronous reads, idempotent duplicate responses
    201 Created    — synchronous resource creation

- All new routes MUST have @openapi JSDoc annotations for
  Swagger auto-generation.

- Tests longer than 2s must declare an explicit timeout:
    it('description', async () => { ... }, 15000)

- Add tests for every policy change and every new service method.


# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# 8. ERROR HANDLING
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────

- Always propagate errors with context. Never swallow silently.
- Use early returns for error conditions.
- Prefer structured error types over raw throw new Error('string').
- When fixing a bug, do not introduce unrelated changes.
- For multi-step operations, prefer DB transactions.
  If not possible, ensure each step is idempotent and retryable.
- For critical records (user registration, billing, sessions):
  - Ensure unique constraints exist at the DB level.
  - Ensure the full flow is either transactional or fully idempotent.


# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# 9. SECURITY RULES
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────

- Never commit secrets, API keys, or credentials to source.
  Use .env.example as the reference; never commit .env.
- Pin dependencies — do not upgrade major versions without
  a separate chore: commit and human review.
- Never add a new third-party dependency without checking
  for known vulnerabilities (npm audit or similar).
- Never weaken or remove Helmet, rate-limiting, or Zod
  validation on any existing route.
- Per-IP rate limiting and Zod validation must be in place
  before any business logic runs on new routes.
- Enable egress filtering in production to prevent
  unauthorized outbound requests from workers or LLM handlers.


# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# 10. MINIMAL CHANGE PRINCIPLE
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────

- Only touch the minimal set of files and lines required
  to implement a feature or fix a bug.
- Do NOT make unrelated changes (renaming, extracting,
  formatting) in the same PR or commit.
- When uncertain about scope, stop and ask before expanding.
- After making changes, review for:
  - Race conditions
  - Transactional safety
  - Idempotency
  - Layer boundary violations


# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# 11. PRE-COMMIT CHECKLIST
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────

Before committing or submitting any change, verify:

- [ ] Mutating routes use idempotencyMiddleware where a
      client Idempotency-Key header is expected
- [ ] Webhook routes use webhookDeduplicationGuard or
      inline tryClaimKey() — never isProcessed() + markProcessed()
- [ ] releaseKey() is called on handler failure after key claim
- [ ] Critical background jobs use RetryableJobRunner,
      not raw QueueWorker
- [ ] All LLM calls go through `llmClient` with a `feature` field set
- [ ] Default model is 4o-mini or haiku unless explicitly justified
- [ ] No new process.env reads outside
      src/01-Core/context/RuntimeConfig.ts
- [ ] No new DB, Redis, or Stripe client instantiation
      outside src/05-Infra
- [ ] schema.ts changes have a matching migration in
      Migrator.ts syncTablesFallback()
- [ ] New routes have @openapi annotations
- [ ] No reverse-direction layer imports introduced
- [ ] No // @vibe-safe comments deleted or weakened
- [ ] All relevant tests pass (unit + e2e)
- [ ] No unrelated refactors mixed into this commit
- [ ] No new dependency added without npm audit check
- [ ] Human-only layer changes are flagged with
      // @vibe-safe: HUMAN-CROSS-REVIEW


